WEBVTT

00:02.836 --> 00:05.583
<i>- Previously on St. Elsewhere.
- This boy's dead and gone.</i>

00:05.650 --> 00:10.875
- He's not dead
till I say he's dead.
- I'm here for a sex change.

00:10.942 --> 00:14.345
- [ guffaws ]
- Do you remember what happened
the night you were shot?

00:14.412 --> 00:16.113
I don't even remember
being shot.

00:16.180 --> 00:19.317
- You have no right
to tamper with my life.
- Who am I?

00:19.383 --> 00:22.253
<i>- I don't know.
- Tonight on st. Elsewhere.</i>

00:22.320 --> 00:24.255
No, Peter.
Come here.

00:24.322 --> 00:26.724
Don't, Peter, don't.
Why not?

00:26.791 --> 00:28.993
[ sighs ]
I just don't want it
right now.

00:29.060 --> 00:31.896
I really got interested
in it when I was a woman.

00:31.963 --> 00:34.231
When you were a woman?

00:34.298 --> 00:38.235
Mark, al and I
are lovers.

00:38.302 --> 00:42.239
Any operations to the head,
nose, ears, throat?

00:42.306 --> 00:44.675
No.
Do you pick your nose?

00:44.742 --> 00:48.346
Just enough
to keep it respectable.

00:48.412 --> 00:51.082
<i>He's my son!
Let me go!
Take him out of there!</i>

00:51.148 --> 00:54.485
<i>Keep him away from me!
 Keep him away from me!
Okay, settle down.</i>

02:33.618 --> 02:36.621
Well, today's the day.
Your anniversary?

02:38.856 --> 02:41.058
Bob overland,
Sex change operation.

02:43.694 --> 02:47.331
You're gonna have to
get over this. You're gonna
give yourself an ulcer.

02:47.398 --> 02:51.602
Last night, Ellen and I
discussed it for hours.
Didn't do any good.

02:51.669 --> 02:54.272
I seem to be the only one
that feels this way.

02:54.338 --> 02:56.707
Mark, why don't you go talk
to Hugh Beale?

02:56.774 --> 02:59.977
I talked to Beale
about talking to Bob.

03:00.044 --> 03:02.346
I'm not the crazy one.

03:08.085 --> 03:11.822
Oh, mark.
Uh, I was hoping
if you had a few moments,

03:11.889 --> 03:13.824
we could--
We could talk.

03:17.762 --> 03:19.864
You're busy.

03:19.930 --> 03:22.600
No, that's all right.

03:22.667 --> 03:24.702
What's the problem?

03:24.769 --> 03:27.638
Worried about the operation?
No, not at all.

03:29.240 --> 03:32.009
How do you feel?
I feel confident,
Good.

03:32.076 --> 03:35.212
Except for the fact
that you've been
avoiding me.

03:38.582 --> 03:42.820
Well, I have to tell you, Bob,
as much as I've tried,
I can't come to terms with this.

03:42.887 --> 03:46.524
I think you're making a terrible
mistake, and you'll regret it
for the rest of your life.

03:49.694 --> 03:51.796
Well, at least, uh--

03:51.862 --> 03:55.466
at least it would be
my life, huh?

04:07.511 --> 04:11.182
Well,
I hope someday, mark,
that we can talk--

04:11.248 --> 04:14.118
You know, there's--

04:14.185 --> 04:17.788
There's one thing
that you can't do,

04:17.855 --> 04:21.858
and that's to make
new old friends.

04:21.926 --> 04:25.763
<i>They're a lot
like hearts, mark.</i>

04:25.830 --> 04:27.765
<i>It's not that easy
to replace them.</i>

04:27.832 --> 04:29.567
Hmm?

04:41.779 --> 04:43.848
Good Morning.
Hiya, Dr. Chandler.

04:43.914 --> 04:46.651
You hear anything lately
from the police?
They find who shot me?

04:46.717 --> 04:50.054
No, no leads yet.
Given any more thought
to what Sterling means?

04:50.121 --> 04:53.991
"No, no leads yet."
Your parents will be here
in a little while.

04:54.058 --> 04:56.861
What'd you say my name was?
David Steward?

04:56.927 --> 04:58.863
Yes.
I don't like it.

04:58.929 --> 05:01.132
I've gotten used to
John Doe number 12.

05:01.198 --> 05:05.202
Listen. I've seen pictures,
fingerprints, blood type--
Everything matches.

05:05.269 --> 05:08.639
You are David Steward
from port dalhousie
in Ontario, Canada.

05:08.706 --> 05:10.641
And these people
are your parents.

05:10.708 --> 05:13.077
I believe you,
it's just that--
what?

05:15.880 --> 05:17.815
I prayed last night that
a Miracle would happen.

05:17.882 --> 05:20.785
That somehow when I see them,
it will all Click into place.

05:20.851 --> 05:24.689
The Miracle
is that you're still alive.

05:24.755 --> 05:26.958
Now everything else is
gonna be a long, slow ride.

05:27.024 --> 05:30.494
I know.
When they get here,
I'll be ready.

05:36.233 --> 05:39.570
You see him, man?
No, I-I don't.

05:39.637 --> 05:42.440
Well, keep lookin', man.
He's in there.

05:42.506 --> 05:47.545
No, Mr. Singer, I'm sorry.
You have everything else
in your ear but an ant.

05:47.612 --> 05:49.513
When's the last time
you used a washcloth?

05:52.116 --> 05:55.353
Pete, your wife's
on the phone.

05:55.419 --> 05:57.355
I'll be right there.
Okay.

05:57.421 --> 06:00.424
Now don't do that.

06:00.491 --> 06:02.426
It's raw enough
in there already.

06:10.568 --> 06:13.337
Hello.

06:13.404 --> 06:15.539
Yeah, Yeah.

06:15.606 --> 06:18.509
No, no, no, that's okay.
That's okay.

06:18.576 --> 06:22.280
Yeah, he told me.
It's just that I was
working late, you know,

06:22.346 --> 06:25.850
and I thought it would be
too late to call you
when I got off.

06:27.218 --> 06:29.120
Yeah?

06:31.222 --> 06:35.526
Yeah, listen.
I've been thinking
the same thing myself.

06:35.593 --> 06:39.063
And, uh-- Mm-Hmm.

06:40.898 --> 06:44.669
Okay, uh-- okay,
I can get an hour off
this afternoon sometime.

06:44.735 --> 06:46.771
If that's, you know--

06:46.837 --> 06:49.674
Yeah. About 2:00.

06:49.740 --> 06:51.842
Okay, that sounds
real Good.

06:51.909 --> 06:56.180
Okey-Dokey.
All right. Bye-Bye.

06:56.247 --> 06:59.717
[ Clears Throat ]
that was Myra.

07:03.154 --> 07:07.091
I gotta go over there
to pick up a few things.

07:07.158 --> 07:11.929
I mean, I got, like,
two pair of socks
and three shirts.

07:11.996 --> 07:14.665
<i>[ siren wailing in distance ]
it's ridiculous, you know.</i>

07:20.304 --> 07:22.239
I gotta get back in there.

07:24.342 --> 07:27.144
<i>[ woman on P.A. ]
Mrs. Weller, please report
to your room.</i>

07:27.211 --> 07:29.513
<i>Mrs. Weller, to your room.</i>

07:35.286 --> 07:37.188
Okay, let's see how it is.

07:45.396 --> 07:47.331
Oh, there's still a little.

07:47.398 --> 07:49.333
So, I'll bleed to death.

07:49.400 --> 07:52.837
Mr. Heller,
in the great majority of cases,
the bleeding contains itself.

07:52.903 --> 07:54.872
So tell my Corpuscles.

07:54.939 --> 07:57.942
It's never been
this bad before?
Has it ever been this bad?

07:58.009 --> 08:01.379
Will you make it stop
already?

08:01.445 --> 08:05.383
How's your general health?
Okay?
Okay? I'm 77 years old.

08:05.449 --> 08:09.887
I pee too much.
I sleep too little.
What's okay?

08:09.954 --> 08:11.956
Any recent
sudden weight loss?

08:12.023 --> 08:15.092
I have been a contractor
for 51 years,

08:15.159 --> 08:18.129
and I have never lost
one day to a nosebleed.

08:18.195 --> 08:22.300
Now Let's get with it,
or find somebody who can.

08:24.268 --> 08:26.904
I'm sorry.

08:26.971 --> 08:30.174
Ever since I come in here,
I've been gripin' and bleedin'.

08:31.709 --> 08:34.211
I just have no energy.

08:34.278 --> 08:38.182
I don't even
have enough to make
a dirty-Old-Man pass at you.

08:40.083 --> 08:43.788
Any operations to the head,
nose, ears, throat?

08:43.854 --> 08:46.123
No.
Do you pick your nose?

08:46.190 --> 08:49.527
Just enough to keep it
respectable.

08:51.629 --> 08:53.731
What kind of contracting?

08:53.798 --> 08:59.203
Oh, uh, remodeling.
You know, adding on.
I like to use my hands.

08:59.270 --> 09:03.074
Anything a plumber,
an electrician or a Mason
can do, I can do myself.

09:03.140 --> 09:06.477
I still spend
a couple hours a week
helping out my kid.

09:06.544 --> 09:10.381
My Kid.
He's 53 years old.

09:10.448 --> 09:13.050
That's terrific.

09:13.117 --> 09:15.486
Yeah, all I do now
is walk around the house...

09:15.553 --> 09:20.725
and leave a Trail
of blood behind me,
like a snail.

09:20.791 --> 09:22.893
Well, Mr. Heller,
this may be nothing at all.

09:22.960 --> 09:26.163
The only way
we can find out for sure
is to run some tests on you.

09:26.230 --> 09:28.599
Is that okay?
Oh, sure, Sure.

09:28.666 --> 09:30.901
We're gonna find out
what's in there, huh?
Right.

09:33.337 --> 09:36.607
Two weeks ago,
your son was admitted
to the emergency room.

09:36.674 --> 09:39.010
Now, he'd had been shot here
with a hollow-Point bullet,

09:39.076 --> 09:41.212
which splintered
through his body.

09:41.279 --> 09:44.382
Now, his heart Stopped.
His left lung collapsed.

09:44.448 --> 09:49.086
He lost an enormous amount
of blood which cut off
the oxygen supply to his brain.

09:49.153 --> 09:54.792
Now, the bullet holes
in his heart, liver
and left Kidney were sutured.

09:54.859 --> 09:56.794
We had to remove
his spleen.

09:56.861 --> 09:58.929
And we put in
a temporary colostomy.

09:58.996 --> 10:01.599
Clinically,
he was dead.

10:01.666 --> 10:06.570
My god, I had no idea
of the extent of his injuries.

10:06.637 --> 10:08.839
Michael, please,
sit down.

10:08.906 --> 10:12.243
But you said he's
going to be all right.

10:12.310 --> 10:14.779
Yes. Yes, he is.
The reason I'm telling you
all this...

10:14.845 --> 10:18.482
is so that you'll understand
what a trauma your boy
has been through...

10:18.549 --> 10:21.619
and what a remarkable
recovery he's made.

10:21.686 --> 10:24.722
<i>[ knocking ]
yes, come in.</i>

10:24.789 --> 10:27.191
Ah, Dr. Chandler.
Mr. And Mrs. Steward.

10:27.258 --> 10:30.194
Dr. Chandler-- He's been
in charge of David's case
since he left surgery.

10:30.261 --> 10:32.763
Oh. How do you do?
How are you?
Mr. Steward.

10:32.830 --> 10:35.766
Hello. How's he doing?
Oh, very well,
considering.

10:35.833 --> 10:37.768
He's a great kid.

10:37.835 --> 10:41.205
The major problem,
as you know, is he suffered
a complete loss of memory...

10:41.272 --> 10:43.474
of everything
prior to his waking up
here at the hospital.

10:43.541 --> 10:48.346
How long will it be
before my son is cured
of this amnesia?

10:48.412 --> 10:51.849
Well, Mr. Steward,
I think we should tell you
that, uh,

10:51.916 --> 10:54.151
<i>David may Never
recover his memory.</i>

10:54.218 --> 10:58.255
Or if he does, it may
be just a partial recovery.
We don't know.

10:58.322 --> 11:01.459
But we are working
together every day
to try and get it back.

11:01.525 --> 11:03.260
I see.

11:03.327 --> 11:06.464
I think you should know
that the entire hospital
is behind David.

11:06.530 --> 11:08.633
We all feel we have
a personal stake in him.

11:08.699 --> 11:12.136
<i>He's a tremendous kid,
and we're doing everything
that we can.</i>

11:12.203 --> 11:15.940
I know this is
an awful lot of information
to absorb so quickly,

11:16.007 --> 11:18.509
so if you wanna just think
about things before
you go see David--

11:18.576 --> 11:22.513
He's been gone 13 months.
It's a long time.

11:22.580 --> 11:25.716
<i>I don't wanna
wait any longer.
Right.</i>

11:25.783 --> 11:27.551
I'll show you the way.

11:27.618 --> 11:30.655
Now, if there's anything
you wanna know about
his medical care,

11:30.721 --> 11:33.424
or if there's anything at all
I can do for you,
please let me know.

11:33.491 --> 11:36.294
Thank you very much,
Doctor.

11:36.360 --> 11:38.262
Thank you.
Certainly.

11:45.469 --> 11:49.006
Dr. Chandler, are you aware
that I'm David's stepmother?

11:49.073 --> 11:51.676
Yes. I read that
in the police report.

11:51.742 --> 11:55.379
Lizzie, David's mother,
died about four years ago.

11:55.446 --> 11:57.915
Of what?
Botulism.

11:59.417 --> 12:01.452
Well, we're
right in here.

12:01.519 --> 12:06.257
Michael and I
were married nine months
after Lizzie's death.

12:06.324 --> 12:09.894
I don't think David
Fully accepted
Our marriage ever.

12:09.961 --> 12:12.930
As a matter of fact,
I think he thought
that we betrayed his mother.

12:12.997 --> 12:15.666
That's not True.
Not True.

12:15.733 --> 12:19.170
We've talked about this before.
I don't think he has
any problem with that.

12:19.236 --> 12:21.172
All right.
Maybe you're right.

12:21.238 --> 12:24.442
Maybe it's just a feeling
that I have.

12:24.508 --> 12:26.444
David's always been
very sweet to me.

12:26.510 --> 12:30.748
It's just--
Well, his mother's death
was quite a blow to him.

12:30.815 --> 12:33.384
And to me too.
We were great friends.

12:35.553 --> 12:39.590
Well, um, while David
was in deep relaxation,

12:39.657 --> 12:41.926
he remembered
one WORD: Sterling.

12:41.993 --> 12:44.462
Does that mean anything
to either one of you?

12:44.528 --> 12:48.032
- No. Kate?
- Sterling? No.

12:48.099 --> 12:52.236
Well, if anything comes to mind,
no matter how insignificant,
please let me know.

12:52.303 --> 12:54.872
<i>[ Michael ]
All right.
I'll go get David.</i>

12:54.939 --> 12:59.710
Oh, by the way,
don't expect him
to recognize you right off.

12:59.777 --> 13:01.712
Don't push too fast.
Go easy.

13:01.779 --> 13:05.283
<i>He's still
very disoriented, weak
and still Traumatized.</i>

13:05.349 --> 13:07.251
- We understand.
- Good.

13:19.130 --> 13:21.032
That's him.

13:31.842 --> 13:34.378
Can I?
Sure.
Go right ahead.

13:40.584 --> 13:44.822
[ chuckles ]
you look fine.
How do you feel?

13:44.889 --> 13:46.824
When they told me
what you've been through--

13:50.828 --> 13:53.130
Hello, David.

13:54.899 --> 13:56.834
I don't know you,
you know.

13:56.901 --> 13:59.470
I told you it would take
some time, David.

13:59.537 --> 14:02.239
Come on, come on.
We've got a lot
to talk about.

14:02.306 --> 14:04.642
Yes, well, I'll see you
in a little while.
Dr. Chandler.

14:04.709 --> 14:07.745
Yes, David.
When am I due
in physical therapy?

14:07.812 --> 14:11.816
Not for a couple of hours.
You take all the time you want.

14:15.886 --> 14:17.822
Dr. Westphall?
Can I have a second?

14:17.888 --> 14:21.025
Sure. Come on in.

14:21.092 --> 14:25.529
I've got a patient in the E.R.--
chronic nosebleeder-- but I
can't find anything to treat.

14:25.596 --> 14:28.032
What's
the platelet count?
Adequate, 250,000.

14:28.099 --> 14:30.034
The function
is near 100%.

14:30.101 --> 14:32.536
Did you order
a coagulation profile?

14:32.603 --> 14:36.040
It showed a p.T./P.P.T.
Less than one point off
the standard control.

14:36.107 --> 14:39.043
I also did a blood smear.
Normal differential.

14:39.110 --> 14:41.812
The cells were mature,
normal in shape, size and Color.

14:41.879 --> 14:44.582
Hmm.
That's interesting,
isn't it?

14:44.649 --> 14:46.951
What about his family?
He's a widower.

14:47.018 --> 14:50.121
No, no, I mean
any of his relatives
have the same complaint?

14:50.187 --> 14:52.490
I don't know.
Why don't you know?

14:52.556 --> 14:54.492
I didn't check.

14:54.558 --> 14:58.095
<i>Wendy, diagnosis is less
of a Gamble if you start
at the beginning.</i>

14:58.162 --> 15:00.831
<i>You didn't take
an adequate history, right?
I thought I did.</i>

15:00.898 --> 15:02.833
You should know by now...

15:02.900 --> 15:05.903
how important it is
to get a complete
family medical history.

15:05.970 --> 15:09.573
You ask him: Mother and father
Alive or dead? If they're dead,
what did they die of?

15:09.640 --> 15:14.345
<i>Brothers and sisters--
Did any of them die?
Also, why? Of what?</i>

15:14.412 --> 15:16.714
<i>You've got to delve
into this thing
as far as you have to go.</i>

15:16.781 --> 15:20.184
Well, I used what we had on him.
He wasn't my patient the first
time he came in.

15:20.251 --> 15:23.621
Well, that's just fine.
Why don't you tell him that?
I'm sure he'll understand.

15:23.688 --> 15:26.123
But I suggest
you get that history
and work from it.

15:26.190 --> 15:30.294
<i>Otherwise both you
and your patient are in for
a pretty rough time, right?</i>

15:30.361 --> 15:32.596
Right.

15:37.501 --> 15:40.571
<i>[ Beale ] I'm preparing
for a lecture that I'm doing
tomorrow at harvard...</i>

15:40.638 --> 15:45.676
<i>for some young medical students
who are thinking about
going into psychiatry.</i>

15:45.743 --> 15:51.148
<i>You see, the whole idea
is to get a fix on the
hypnagogic Hallucinations.</i>

15:51.215 --> 15:56.287
Look, look, you see?
Each one of these
represents the last image...

15:56.354 --> 15:58.823
that some prisoners
at walpole Correctional had...

15:58.889 --> 16:01.993
just before they fell asleep
each night.

16:02.059 --> 16:04.195
Oh, that's interesting, Hugh.
Yeah.

16:04.261 --> 16:07.131
But all I wanna know is
did you talk to Bob overland?

16:07.198 --> 16:09.667
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, I did.

16:09.734 --> 16:12.169
He's feeling fragged, right?

16:12.236 --> 16:16.007
It's a midlife crisis.
Does he think he's the only one?

16:16.073 --> 16:19.977
In my opinion, Bob is
handling the situation
very Well.

16:20.044 --> 16:24.115
[ scoffs ]
I think you're the one
with the problem, mark.

16:24.181 --> 16:27.718
Me?
Yeah.

16:27.785 --> 16:30.154
I do not have a problem.

16:30.221 --> 16:32.623
You and Bob
are very old friends.

16:32.690 --> 16:35.826
You have
similar backgrounds,
similar families,

16:35.893 --> 16:39.196
similar educations,
similar mind-Sets.

16:39.263 --> 16:42.199
But I'm not about
to get my thing cut off.

16:42.266 --> 16:44.702
There is
that one difference, yes.

16:44.769 --> 16:48.239
I think you have to admit,
however, that what he's doing
takes a whole lot of Courage.

16:48.306 --> 16:51.842
Yes, I admit that.
Bob's always had
a lot of courage,

16:51.909 --> 16:55.146
integrity, strength.

16:55.212 --> 16:58.349
Like those guys up THERE:
Daniel Boone,

16:58.416 --> 17:02.353
natty bumppo, hawkeye.

17:02.420 --> 17:06.123
What the hell am I talking
about? Will you turn
this damn thing off?

17:06.190 --> 17:08.425
I'm trying to have
an intelligent conversation,

17:08.492 --> 17:10.761
and you keep showing me
these stupid slides.

17:10.828 --> 17:13.464
All right.
All right.

17:13.531 --> 17:15.433
Look.

17:17.233 --> 17:21.071
Bob is one of your oldest
and best friends.

17:21.137 --> 17:25.041
You want what's best in life
for him, what'll bring him
happiness, right?

17:25.108 --> 17:27.811
Of course.
All right.

17:27.877 --> 17:33.818
Then try and separate.
Just try and separate
the two Facts.

17:33.884 --> 17:39.290
Number one:
You are personally
offended by this operation.

17:39.357 --> 17:41.592
Now that is a fact.

17:41.659 --> 17:44.128
Number Two:

17:44.195 --> 17:46.797
Bob has lived
his whole life as a man,

17:46.864 --> 17:49.233
and it has not
brought him happiness.

17:49.300 --> 17:51.202
This may just
do it for him.

17:54.171 --> 17:56.073
Separate the two?

17:58.943 --> 18:01.412
So, we were raised
with Three different cultures.

18:01.479 --> 18:05.516
We spoke yiddish at home.
German, we knew.
And american, right?

18:05.583 --> 18:07.985
Does anyone else
in your family
have nosebleeds?

18:08.052 --> 18:10.221
Sure.
Yes?

18:10.288 --> 18:12.223
Doesn't everybody
have nosebleeds?

18:12.290 --> 18:15.192
Many people do,
but not everybody does.

18:15.259 --> 18:19.196
Oh. Yeah,
my grandpa Nathan.

18:19.263 --> 18:21.232
That was my mother's father.

18:21.299 --> 18:23.467
I remember him
with a big handkerchief,

18:23.534 --> 18:26.103
holding it over his face
and it was all bloody.

18:26.170 --> 18:30.574
We'd just got off
